Tips on Building Shiny Apps

Elgar Teo

May 11, 2021

Shiny is a powerful framework that allows you to create interactive web applications using just the R language. Though there are some common pitfalls/hassles when building Shiny applications. This guide aims to help you avoid them.

Formatting

Since it is very likely that your code would be in a nested structure that involves a bunch of parentheses one inside another, it is not uncommon for one to encounter to following error message when developing a Shiny app:

This Error in sourcing message likely indicates that there are some extra or missing symbols in your code like an redundant comma (e.g., fluidRow(uiOutput("header"), uiOutput("post_c"),)) or a missing closing parenthesis (e.g., fluidRow(uiOutput("header"), uiOutput("post_c")).

Keeping the formatting of your code clean can help avoid this type of error. Imagine that you want to construct a Shiny app that comprises of two rows with two and three boxes respectively:

Compare the two versions ui.R that generates the layout above:

## Version A:
ui <- dashboardPage(dashboardHeader(title = "Row layout"),dashboardSidebar(),
  dashboardBody(fluidRow(box(title = "Box title", "Box content"),box(status = "warning", "Box content")),
fluidRow(
box(title = "Title 1", width = 4, solidHeader = TRUE, status = "primary","Box content"),box(title = "Title 2", width = 4, solidHeader = TRUE,"Box content"
),box(title = "Title 1", width = 4, solidHeader = TRUE, status = "warning","Box content"))))

## Version B
ui <- dashboardPage(
  dashboardHeader(title = "Row layout"),
  dashboardSidebar(),
  dashboardBody(
    fluidRow(
      box(title = "Box title", "Box content"),
      box(status = "warning", "Box content")
    ),
    
    fluidRow(
      box(
        title = "Title 1", width = 4, solidHeader = TRUE, status = "primary",
        "Box content"
        ),
      box(
        title = "Title 2", width = 4, solidHeader = TRUE,
        "Box content"
      ),
      box(
        title = "Title 1", width = 4, solidHeader = TRUE, status = "warning",
        "Box content"
      )
    )
  )
)

Both versions work. But Version B is apparently easier to comprehend as you can easily tell that the structure of the interface. In contrast, version A is just a mess. Worse of all, if you carelessly mistyped an extra comma or forgot a closing parenthesis, it would be immensely difficult for you to track down the culprit of the error.

From the example above, we can derive several rules in formatting:

  1. If you are to insert a long section of code into a parenthesis, do so in an indented new line.

  2. If there are way too many parameters inside a function, split them into multiple lines.

  3. Always end a line with (, ) or ,.

Following these rules is easier than you think. RStudios editor automatically indents the code so you can easily format your code just by using the Backspace and Enter key:

Another useful feature of RStudio is its ability to track the pairs of parenthesis. When you place the text cursor right after a parenthesis, the corresponding paired parenthesis will be highlighted:

This can help you avoid missing parenthesis.

shinydashboard

In the class, we introduced shinydashboard, a package that offers an easy-to-use framework for building Shiny apps. The fluidRow() function that arranges UI components in row and the valueBoxOutput()/renderValueBox() functions that render value boxes are part of the features provided by shinydashboard.

We only managed to scratch on the surface of shinydashboard in the class. If you are interested in implementing other features provided by the package such as a column-based layout and info boxes, you can refer to its very intuitive documentation here.

Ploting graphs

In the in-class example, we introduced the way to plot Plotly graphs using the plotlyOutput()/renderPlotly() functions. Beside Plotly graphs, you can also incorporate other graphics such as word cloud or leaflet maps into a Shiny app.

To understand how to insert graphics into R, it is better to understand first how R deals with graphs. There are two types of graphsstatic and interactive. Static graphs are basically images. When you generate a static graph in RStudio, it is shown in the Plots tab. Examples of static graphs are word clouds generated by the package wordcloud and plots created by ggplot2. On the other hand, interactive graphs are HTML-based. When you generate a interactive graph in RStudio, it is shown in the Viewer panel. Examples of interactive graphs are Plotly graphs, word clouds generated by the package wordcloud2 and maps by leaflet.

To insert a static graph in a Shiny app, you can use the plotOutput()/renderPlot() functions. The way of using it is simple: you put the placeholder function plotOutput() in ui.R to indicate where the plot should be shown, and then define how the graph should be plotted inside renderPlot() in server.R. For example, if we want to plot a static word cloud:

## ui.R
ui <- dashboardPage(
  dashboardHeader(title = "Word Cloud"),
  dashboardSidebar(),
  dashboardBody(
    fluidRow(
      box(title = "Word Cloud", plotOutput("plot"))
    )
  )
)
## server.R
output$plot <- renderPlot({
  # a very simple word cloud that contains two words
  data <- data.frame(
    words = c("hello", "world"),
    freq = c(30, 20)
  )
  wordcloud(words = data$words, freq = data$freq)
})

plotOutput()/renderPlot() can only be used to render static graphs. If you want to integrate interactive graphs in Shiny, you need to use the special functions provided by the package that generate the interactive graphs. For instance, as shown in the in-class example, plotly provides the plotlyOutput()/renderPlotly() functions for inserting Plotly graphs in Shiny. Similarly, wordcloud2 provides the wordcloud2Output()/renderWordcloud2() functions and leaflet provides the leafletOutput()/renderLeaflet() functions for inserting interactive word clouds and maps respectively. The principle of using these functions are the same. For example, if you want to plot a interactive word cloud:

## ui.R
ui <- dashboardPage(
  dashboardHeader(title = "Word Cloud"),
  dashboardSidebar(),
  dashboardBody(
    fluidRow(
      box(title = "Word Cloud", wordcloud2Output("plot"))
    )
  )
)
## server.R
output$plot <- renderWordcloud2({
  # a very simple word cloud that contains two words
  data <- data.frame(
    words = c("hello", "world"),
    freq = c(30, 20)
  )
  wordcloud2(data)
})

leaflets documentation offers a very intuitive tutorial on how to insert maps in Shiny. Those whore interested can have a read here.

Responsive Data Loading

Assignment 5 requires you to construct a dashboard that analyses seven different hashtags, meaning that your Shiny app needs to at least allow the user to select which hashtag theyd like to analyse in the dashboard. The in-class example has actually demonstrated how to achieve this feature in ui_part2.R and server_part2.R, but since we didnt have time to discuss this in the class due to time constraints, Ill briefly talk about it here.

The example here is based on the in-class sample code which is a dashboard for analysing two Twitter accounts. The same concept can be applied to creating a dashboard that can analyse multiple hashtags.

Lets look at first how the in-class sample manages to analyse one Twitter account. The following is an excerpt from server_part1.R:

server <- function(input, output) {

  ip_handle <- readRDS("jmschku_handle.rds")
  ip_timeline <- readRDS("jmschku_timeline.rds")
  ip_folls_data <- readRDS("jmschku_folls_data.rds")

  output$handle_name <- renderText({
    ip_handle$screen_name
  })
  ### ...more code follows...
}

From the code above, we can understand that the Shiny app first loads the pre-downloaded data from the three RDS files. Afterwards, each output code block, e.g., output$handle_name, handles the various type of analysis and visualisation by using the data loaded, i.e., ip_handle, ip_timeline and ip_folls_data.

To allow the user to choose which Twitter account they want to analyse, we can modify the code such that the app can load the corresponding RDS files of the selected Twitter account. This is precisely what ui_part2.R and server_part2.R do.

Lets look at ui_part2.R first:

ui <- dashboardPage(
  dashboardHeader(title = textOutput("handle_name")),
  dashboardSidebar(
    mainPanel(
      uiOutput("profile_pic"),
      sliderInput("pct_followers", "Percentile of its followers' followers count to view:", 0, 100, 50),
      selectInput("acc", "Choose an account:", choices = c("jmschku", "keithrichburg")),
      width = 12     
    )
  ),
  dashboardBody(
    ### ...more code follows...
  )
)

Note the selectInput(...). This creates a dropdown box that allows the user to pick the account they want to analyse, which in this case are either jmschku or keithrichburg.

But how do we make the Shiny app loads the correct RDS file depending on what the user has selected? Refer to the server_part2.R:

server <- function(input, output) {

  ip_handle <- reactive({
    switch(input$acc,"jmschku" = readRDS("jmschku_handle.rds"),"keithrichburg" = readRDS("keithrichburg_handle.rds"))
  })

  ip_timeline <- reactive({
    switch(input$acc,"jmschku" = readRDS("jmschku_timeline.rds"),"keithrichburg" = readRDS("keithrichburg_timeline.rds"))
  })

  ip_folls_data <- reactive({
    switch(input$acc,"jmschku" = readRDS("jmschku_folls_data.rds"),"keithrichburg" = readRDS("keithrichburg_folls_data.rds"))
  })

  output$handle_name <- renderText({
    ip_handle <- ip_handle()
    ip_handle$screen_name
  })
  ### ...more code follows...
}

Compared with server_part1.R, the lines that load the RDS files now look more complicated. Here is how the magic works. Lets focus on ip_handle first:

ip_handle <- reactive({
  switch(input$acc,"jmschku" = readRDS("jmschku_handle.rds"),"keithrichburg" = readRDS("keithrichburg_handle.rds"))
})

First of all, the value that the user has selected in the dropdown box can be accessed at input$acc. The switch(...) command is very similar to a ifelse if statement. It evaluates the value of the first argument, in this case input$acc which is the user-selected account name, and determine which line should be run. For instance, if the user selected jmschku, input$acc becomes jmschku, and thus the second argument, which is "jmschku" = readRDS("jmschku_handle.rds"), is run. This loads jmschku_handle.rds and assigns it as ip_handle.

If you still do not understand, consider this ifelse if version, which does exactly the same thing:

ip_handle <- reactive({
  if (input$acc == "jmschku") {
    readRDS("jmschku_handle.rds")
  } else if (input$acc == "keithrichburg") {
    readRDS("keithrichburg_handle.rds")
  }
})

In the other words, instead of being a fixed data of a specific Twitter account, ip_handle is a responsive data of whatever Twitter account selected by the user. If the user picks jmschku, ip_handle contains the account data of jmschku. If the user picks keithrichburg, ip_handle contains the account data of keithrichburg.

Note the reactive({...}). This is required because this is a Shiny app.

The same idea goes for ip_timeline and ip_folls_data.

switch() accepts unlimited number of conditions. If there are more options for the user to choose from, you can simply extend the list:

ip_handle <- reactive({
  switch(input$acc,
         "jmschku" = readRDS("jmschku_handle.rds"),
         "keithrichburg" = readRDS("keithrichburg_handle.rds"),
         "fukingwa" = readRDS("fukingwa_handle.rds"),
         "MasatoKJ" = readRDS("MasatoKJ_handle.rds"))
})

One thing to be aware of is that we need one extra line of code in each output block:

server <- function(input, output) {
  ### ...more code follows...
  output$handle_name <- renderText({
    ip_handle <- ip_handle() # <--------------Extra line required!
    ip_handle$screen_name
  })

  output$statu_c <- renderValueBox({
    ip_handle <- ip_handle() # <--------------Extra line required!
    valueBox(
      ip_handle$statuses_count, "Statuses Count", icon = icon("list"),
      color = "yellow"
    )
  })

  output$pct_folls <- renderValueBox({
    ip_folls_data <- ip_folls_data() # <--------------Extra line required!
    valueBox(
      round(quantile(ip_folls_data$followers_count,input$pct_followers/100),2), paste(input$pct_followers," percetile of its Followers' Followers count"), icon = icon("list"),
      color = "blue"
    )
  })
  ### ...more code follows...
}

If you need to use the data ip_handle in an output block, you need to insert the line ip_handle <- ip_handle(). If you need to use the data ip_folls_data, insert the line ip_folls_data <- ip_folls_data(). A short answer to why this is required because ip_handle, ip_timeline and ip_folls_data are responsive data that reacts to user input, and this extra line of code updates the data to reflect changes in the user input.

From the explanation above, we now know how to load data in response to user input. You can apply the same concept in constructing your assignment 5. More specifically, you need to download and save the tweets of the seven hashtags as RDS files, and then allow the Shiny app to read any of these files based on user input.
